{{short description|2012 book by Rebecca MacKinnon}} {{Infobox book |italic title =force | name = Consent of the Networked: The Worldwide Struggle for Internet Freedom | image = Consent of the Networked book cover.jpg | caption = | author = [[Rebecca MacKinnon]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = | series = | subject = [[Internet censorship]] | genre = | publisher = [[Basic Books]] | pub_date = 2012 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 294 | isbn = 978-0-465-02442-1 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Consent of the Networked: The Worldwide Struggle for Internet Freedom''''' is a book written by [[Rebecca MacKinnon]] and released in 2012. It discusses [[internet censorship]] and the ways in which companies which manage internet communication are assuming responsibilities formerly held by governments.
==Reviews== The review published in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' described ''Consent of the Networked'' as "an excellent survey of the Internet's major fault lines".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204369404577207363346183978 |title=Book Review: Consent of the Networked - WSJ.com |first=Luke |last=Allnutt |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=15 February 2012 |location=New York |issn=0099-9660 |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> [[John Naughton]]'s review in ''[[The Guardian]]'' said that the book will "find its way on to reading lists in [[political science]]" for those interested in the relationship between Internet and the government.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/feb/26/internet-companies-power-politics-freedom |title=Tech giants have power to be political masters as well as our web ones |author=[[John Naughton]] |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 February 2012 |location=London |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> Rachel Bridgewater's review in the [[Library Journal]] states, "She uses many real-life examples and anecdotes to illustrate the complex web of policy and technical infrastructure that allows governments and corporate interests to censor, surveil, and otherwise impede free expression and individual liberty."<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Consent of the Networked: The Worldwide Struggle for Internet Freedom|last = Bridgewater|first = Rachel|date = 2012|journal = Library Journal|doi = |pmid = }}</ref>
